          "title": "The honorable vessel and the gentle correction (2:20-26)",
          "body": "The chapter's closing image is domestic: a great house with mixed vessels — gold, silver, wood, clay; some for honor, some for dishonor (2:20). The believer who cleanses himself becomes a vessel *for honor, sanctified, useful to the Master, prepared for every good work* (2:21). The cleansing is moral (flee youthful lusts, 2:22) and relational (pursue righteousness, faith, love, peace *with those who call on the Lord from a pure heart*, 2:22). The chapter closes with the posture toward opponents (2:23-26) — refuse foolish speculations, do not be quarrelsome, be kind, able to teach, patient when wronged, correcting with *gentleness* (*prautes*), trusting that God may grant repentance leading to knowledge of the truth, and that the opponent may *come to his senses* and escape the *devil's snare*. Opponents are not enemies to be destroyed but captives to be rescued."
